Liquid clustering — the modern replacement for partitioning plus zorder.

Classic delta layouts force a one-time decision. Do you partition by transaction date, or by customer id? Get it wrong, and you're stuck — re-partitioning a terabyte-scale table is a full rewrite.

Liquid clustering replaces both partitioning and zorder with a single property. You declare which columns the table is clustered on, and delta organises the data into clusters that can be incrementally re-balanced. The key win is that you can change the cluster keys later without rewriting the world.

So what do you give up, and what do you gain? You give up the explicit directory-style partition structure. In return you gain three things — no small-files-per-partition problem, no skew when one partition is a hundred times larger than another, and the ability to evolve your clustering as query patterns change.

For the exam, remember the recommendation. Liquid clustering is recommended for new delta tables, and it comes up again in the optimization notebook.
